{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"01165fc0-44e0-11ed-8b10-18c34f15efc1","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rowsAreFullWidth":false,"backgroundImageUrl":"","rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"869d8452-b65a-463b-82f1-e9d4484998ef","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Excessive Trading and Overconfidence","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"2b5e54f8-4287-43cf-89bd-dc66e8c4d280"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"2c46ff71-3f24-4e92-ac1e-c74a25e83a51","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Trading is expensive; you must pay commissions on top of the difference between the bid and ask price, called the ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"spread","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":". Given how hard it should be to identify over- and undervalued stocks, you might then expect individual investors to take a conservative approach to trading. However, in an influential study of the trading behavior of individual investors that held accounts at a discount brokerage, researchers Brad Barber and Terrance Odean found that individual investors tend to trade very actively, with average turnover almost 50% above the average of all investors including institutions during the time period of their study.","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"01c261cf-78ba-43ee-9906-8e377d79233e","stage":{"ref":"ab40a007-673e-4606-af58-6b10d9d18905","sections":[{"ref":"bff4aa57-e5ee-468f-b55c-ec8d7e0c6df3","rows":[{"ref":"b2fc11fc-cd5c-462b-b712-18c60298a0c3","columns":[{"ref":"26c4fd6d-ebd9-4f50-963f-9bf3f20f7916","stageElements":[{"ref":"61cf790a-44d4-45a5-a1b6-9ecfff3ee36f","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"0f35b88d-efb6-4670-b078-0d47990db9ac","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"b875b2fb-4d4f-415c-93c5-9f8153830440","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"B. Barber and T. Odean, “Trading Is Hazardous to Your Wealth: The Common Stock Investment Performance of Individual Investors,” ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"Journal of Finance","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" 55 (2000) 773–806.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"4","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"footnote","ref":"f8a507a0-3b3d-4a6f-a5d6-c2095ec343af"}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"a98f95a1-51f8-41bf-ba2c-e3cc66d90da7"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"dea3e531-b0c6-49d7-8182-cdc8e2523f85","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"What might explain this trading behavior? Psychologists have known since the 1960s that uninformed individuals tend to overestimate the precision of their knowledge. For example, many sports fans sitting in the stands confidently second-guess the coaching decisions on the field, truly believing that they can do a better job. In finance we call investors’ presumptuousness of their ability to beat the market by overtrading the ","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"749552ca-673e-4f5c-95c6-11a336fd0a36","stage":{"ref":"df657475-8d18-4cdc-bf20-c0a00a659b67","sections":[{"ref":"9de6f467-4f43-49a0-b08c-227e247eb5c7","rows":[{"ref":"28c4d741-cf90-4829-a38b-7a50195e27fb","columns":[{"ref":"0dd0bfff-c81d-49ec-9919-cee767494491","stageElements":[{"ref":"3b7f8005-3853-4992-a9d4-3513f82ef883","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"7148bdba-9a64-4979-bbc4-936cc9e1beed","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"7c80b2c2-0a5c-4be6-a3c4-d1c871143567","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"The tendency of individual investors to trade too much based on the mistaken belief that they can pick winners and losers better than investment professionals.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"overconfidence hypothesis","marks":[{"type":"bold"}]}],"object":"inline","type":"key-term","ref":"13a2fb04-2d66-4221-b0f9-9a21b58d45af"},{"object":"text","text":". Barber and Odean hypothesized that this kind of behavior also characterizes individual investment decision making: Like sports fans, individual investors believe they can pick winners and losers when, in fact, they cannot; this overconfidence leads them to trade too much.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"f9ea37a7-f86a-43b0-9fac-c536d5966ebe"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"5fbc4f63-e053-40da-8233-52a04d267192","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"An implication of this overconfidence hypothesis is that, assuming they have no true ability, investors who trade more will not earn higher returns. Instead, their performance will be worse once we take into account the costs of trading (due to both commissions and bid-ask spreads). ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"e8272a7c-e56e-4fc7-96f6-535dc50e8638","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Figure 10.7","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"420445a0-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":" documents precisely this result, showing that much investor trading appears not to be based on rational assessments of performance.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"6da214cc-3a97-4da7-9fa7-0c3ca03701d9"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-image","config":{"url":{"$ambrosia":"aero:asset:upload","urn":"urn:aero:ad5ba1a0-44e0-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","asset":{"urn":"urn:aero:ad5ba1a0-44e0-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","asset":{"assetProvider":"ALFRESCO","id":"ad5ba1a0-44e0-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","assetMediaType":"image","assetVisibility":"GLOBAL","ownerId":"e88133a0-8dc4-11eb-964e-4d7e264c9958","subscriptionId":"f0afd4d0-d2ff-11ea-9998-d57e1e28aca1","alfrescoId":"77197c36-aded-48a3-8264-ff436e276370","name":"FG_10_007.jpg","version":"2.0","lastModifiedDate":1664998750,"lastSyncDate":1665085918},"source":{"small":{"width":611,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/ad5ba1a0-44e0-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca/small/5cc6397185627c41324fa8f5aa330a92.jpeg","height":300},"original":{"width":1223,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/ad5ba1a0-44e0-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca/medium/5cc6397185627c41324fa8f5aa330a92.jpeg","height":600},"medium":{"width":1223,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/ad5ba1a0-44e0-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca/medium/5cc6397185627c41324fa8f5aa330a92.jpeg","height":600},"thumb":{"width":306,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/ad5ba1a0-44e0-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca/thumb/5cc6397185627c41324fa8f5aa330a92.jpeg","height":150}},"metadata":{"altText":"","workURN":"","caption":"<p>The plot shows the average annual return (net of commissions and trading costs) for individual investors at a large discount brokerage from 1991&#x2013;1997. Investors are grouped into quintiles based on their average annual turnover. While the least-active investors had slightly (but not significantly) better performance than the S&amp;P 500, performance declined with the rate of turnover.</p>","alfrescoPath":"bronte-e2e-testing-qaint/documentLibrary/BV E2E Test/[10-05-2022] Berk","originalAssetName":"FG_10_007.jpg","longDesc":"","height":"393"}}},"alt":"",